## Do not spend 90 days performing certainty

Your first job is to learn the system you now influence: the people, commitments, constraints, decisions, and promises already in motion. Early leadership is visible in the quality of your questions and the reliability of your follow-through—not in how quickly you replace everything with your own system.

## Days 1–30: make the work and relationships legible

Meet each person, learn what they own, and ask what makes good work easier or harder here. Clarify with your manager what decisions are yours. If you now lead former peers, name the changed role and the boundaries it creates. Establish recurring one-on-ones you can actually keep.

Before changing a process, be able to explain the purpose it serves, who depends on it, and the evidence that it is failing.

## Days 31–60: make expectations observable

Turn vague standards into examples. Give specific positive and adjusting feedback early enough that neither becomes ceremonial. Build a simple decision record: owner, decision, date, dissent, and next review. Repair priority conflict instead of asking people to “own more” inside an incoherent system.

## Days 61–90: grow ownership without disappearing

Choose one meaningful responsibility to delegate with a real outcome, decision rights, constraints, resources, and checkpoints. Coach when the person can own the thinking. Direct when consequence and urgency require it. Review what the team can now do without you—and where your own behavior still creates a bottleneck.

## A useful 90-day record

Keep a short weekly note with four prompts: What did I learn? What did I clarify? What promise did I keep? What will I stop carrying? This is a learning record, not a private score of the team.

> **Boundary:** follow your organization’s HR, legal, security, safety, and reporting processes. A new role does not make you the sole investigator, clinician, or policy authority.
